  "prompt_text": "Write a Python function that finds the longest common subsequence of two strings. Explain your approach.",
  "response_text": "To find the longest common subsequence (LCS) of two strings, we can use dynamic programming. The idea is to build a 2D table where each cell `dp[i][j]` represents the length of the LCS of the substrings `str1[0..i-1]` and `str2[0..j-1]`. Here's how we can implement this:\n\n```python\ndef longest_common_subsequence(str1, str2):\n    m = len(str1)\n    n = len(str2)\n    \n    # Create a 2D array to store lengths of longest common subsequence\n    dp = [[0] * (n + 1) for _ in range(m + 1)]\n    \n    # Build the dp array from bottom up\n    for i in range(1, m + 1):\n        for j in range(1, n + 1):\n            if str1[i - 1] == str2[j - 1]:\n                dp[i][j] = dp[i - 1][j - 1] + 1\n            else:\n                dp[i][j] = max(dp[i - 1][j], dp[i][j - 1])\n    \n    # The length of the LCS is in the bottom-right corner of the matrix\n    lcs_length = dp[m][n]\n    \n    # To get the actual LCS, we can backtrack from dp[m][n]\n    lcs = \"\"\n    while m > 0 and n > 0:\n        if str1[m - 1] == str2[n - 1]:\n            lcs = str1[m - 1] + lcs\n            m -= 1\n            n -= 1\n        elif dp[m - 1][n] > dp[m][n - 1]:\n            m -= 1\n        else:\n            n -= 1\n    \n    return lcs, lcs_length\n\n# Example usage:\nstr1 = \"ABCBDAB\"\nstr2 = \"BDCAB\"\nlcs, length = longest_common_subsequence(str1, str2)\nprint(f\"Longest Common Subsequence: {lcs}\")\nprint(f\"Length of LCS: {length}\")\n```\n\n### Explanation:\n1. **Initialization**: We initialize a 2D list `dp` with dimensions `(m+1) x (n+1)` where `m` and `n` are the lengths of `str1` and `str2`, respectively. Each cell `dp[i][j]` will hold the length of the LCS of `str1[0..i-1]` and `str2[0..j-1]`.\n\n2. **Filling the DP Table**: We iterate through each character of both strings. If characters match (`str1[i-1] == str2[j-1]`), we set `dp[i][",
